{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:18:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:18:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15669"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15669"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0,0.74,0.13,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114399"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15669"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7021"},{"type":"tags","id":"7033"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114399"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe uterine tube (also called the fallopian tube) is an important structure in the female reproductive system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ampulla of the uterine tube?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Narrow medial portion closest to the uterus","Portion that passes through the uterine wall","Widest and longest portion of the tube where fertilisation occurs","Funnel-shaped lateral end with finger-like projections","Muscular sphincter between the ampulla and isthmus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe uterine tube has four distinct anatomical regions. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ewidest and longest portion\u003C/strong\u003E is the ampulla, which comprises approximately 60% of the total tube length and is where fertilisation typically occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enarrow medial portion\u003C/strong\u003E describes the isthmus, which connects to the uterus. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eportion that passes through the uterine wall\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the intramural (or interstitial) part. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efunnel-shaped lateral end\u003C/strong\u003E is the infundibulum, which has fimbriae (finger-like projections) that help capture the ovum. There is no \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscular sphincter\u003C/strong\u003E between the ampulla and isthmus as this represents an incorrect anatomical concept.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ampulla is the widest and longest part of the uterine tube where fertilisation typically occurs.","The uterine tube consists of four parts: infundibulum, ampulla, isthmus, and intramural portion."],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Cheng LK, O\u0027Grady G, Du P, Egbuji JU, Windsor JA, Pullan AJ. Gastrointestinal system. Wiley Interdiscip Rev Syst Biol Med. 2010 Jan-Feb;2(1):65-79. doi: 10.1002/wsbm.19. PMID: 20836011; PMCID: PMC4221587","Kahai P, Mandiga P, Wehrle CJ, Lobo S. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Large Intestine. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing, Treasure Island (FL); 2023. PMID: 29261962","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{